   "source": [
    "# =============================================================================\n",
    "# CORRELATIONS \n",
    "# =============================================================================\n",
    "\n",
    "# checking correlations between numeric features for Pearson and Spearman methods, \n",
    "# and quick top correlations with target to identify which features have the strongest linear and monotonic relationships with the target variable.\n",
    "\n",
    "section(\"Correlation heatmap (numeric)\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Correlation can be dominated by outliers; also checking Spearman in addition to Pearson.\n",
    "num_for_corr = df.drop(columns=[\"ID\"], errors=\"ignore\").select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).copy()\n",
    "\n",
    "corr_pearson = num_for_corr.corr(method=\"pearson\")\n",
    "corr_spearman = num_for_corr.corr(method=\"spearman\")\n",
    "\n",
    "fig = px.imshow(corr_pearson, title=\"Correlation heatmap (Pearson)\", aspect=\"auto\")\n",
    "fig.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "fig = px.imshow(corr_spearman, title=\"Correlation heatmap (Spearman)\", aspect=\"auto\")\n",
    "fig.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "section(\"Top absolute correlations with target (Pearson)\")\n",
    "target_corr = corr_pearson[\"DEFAULT_NEXT_MONTH\"].drop(\"DEFAULT_NEXT_MONTH\").abs().sort_values(ascending=False)\n",
    "print(target_corr.head(20).to_string())\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e74975f2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# What This Table Shows\n",
    "\n",
    "These are **Pearson correlations** between each variable and the target:\n",
    "\n",
    "`DEFAULT_NEXT_MONTH`\n",
    "\n",
    "Correlation range:\n",
    "\n",
    "* -1 to +1\n",
    "* Closer to ±1 = stronger linear relationship\n",
    "* Close to 0 = weak linear relationship\n",
    "\n",
    "# Strongest Predictors\n",
    "\n",
    "Top correlations:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Variable | Correlation |\n",
    "| -------- | ----------- |\n",
    "| PAY_0    | **0.325**   |\n",
    "| PAY_2    | 0.264       |\n",
    "| PAY_3    | 0.235       |\n",
    "| PAY_4    | 0.217       |\n",
    "| PAY_5    | 0.204       |\n",
    "| PAY_6    | 0.187       |\n",
    "\n",
    "### Interpretation:\n",
    "\n",
    "Repayment status variables dominate.\n",
    "\n",
    "PAY_0 alone has correlation ≈ 0.325 — which is very high for behavioural financial data.\n",
    "\n",
    "This confirms:\n",
    "\n",
    "> Recent delinquency is the strongest linear predictor of default.\n",
    "\n",
    "And notice:\n",
    "The correlation decreases as we go further back in time (PAY_6).\n",
    "\n",
    "That makes logical sense:\n",
    "More recent behaviour matters more.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Moderate Predictors\n",
    "\n",
    "| Variable  | Correlation |\n",
    "| --------- | ----------- |\n",
    "| LIMIT_BAL | 0.154       |\n",
    "\n",
    "Credit limit has moderate correlation.\n",
    "\n",
    "Correlation does not mean causation.\n",
    "Higher limit could mean higher exposure or different customer segment.\n",
    "\n",
    "# Weak Predictors\n",
    "\n",
    "Payments:\n",
    "~0.05–0.07\n",
    "\n",
    "Demographics:\n",
    "~0.02–0.04\n",
    "\n",
    "Billing amounts:\n",
    "~0.01–0.02\n",
    "\n",
    "Age:\n",
    "~0.013\n",
    "\n",
    "These are very weak linear relationships.\n",
    "\n",
    "This matches published literature.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Important Limitation\n",
    "\n",
    "Pearson measures **linear relationship only**.\n",
    "\n",
    "Tree-based models (LightGBM/XGBoost):\n",
    "\n",
    "* Capture non-linear patterns\n",
    "* Capture interactions\n",
    "* May extract more signal from weakly correlated features\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "> Pearson correlation analysis confirms that repayment status variables (PAY_0–PAY_6) shows the strongest linear association with default, with PAY_0 showing the highest correlation (r = 0.325). Correlation strength decreases for older delinquency indicators, suggesting that more recent repayment behaviour has greater predictive power. Credit limit demonstrates moderate association (r = 0.154), while demographic variables and billing amounts show weak linear relationships. These findings shows the dominant role of behavioural repayment history in credit risk prediction.\n"
   ]
